{"title_page": "Tracey Neville", "text_new": "{{short description|English netball player and coach}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2017}}\n{{Infobox netball biography\n |name    = Tracey Neville {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MBE}}\n |image   =\n |caption =\n |fullname     = Tracey Anne Neville\n |maidenname   =\n |birth_date  = {{birth date and age|1977|01|21|df=yes}}\n |birth_place = [[Bury, Greater Manchester]], [[England]] <ref name=\"bbc1990s\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/sa/netball/masterclasses/newsid_2869000/2869327.stm|title=Be a world beater with Neville|publisher=news.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"gc2018\">{{cite news|url=https://results.gc2018.com/en/netball/athlete-profile-n6037121-tracey-neville.htm|title=Tracey Neville|publisher=gc2018.com|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n |height       = {{convert|1.73|m|order=flip}} \n |school       = [[Elton High School]]\n |university   = [[University of the West of England, Bristol|University of the West of England]]<br>[[University of Chester]]\n |occupation   =\n |relatives    = [[Neville Neville]] (father)<br>[[Gary Neville]] (brother)<br>[[Phil Neville]] (brother)\n |spouse       =\n |marrieddate  =\n |children     = \n |positions     = WA, GA\n |clubyears1 = 199x-2001\n |clubteam1 = YWCA Bury\n |clubyears2 = 2001-2004\n |clubteam2 = [[Northern Thunder (netball)|Northern Thunder]] \n |clubyears3 = 2007-2008\n |clubteam3 = [[Leeds Carnegie (netball)|Leeds Carnegie]] \n |nationalyears1 = 1996-2008\n |nationalteam1 = [[England national netball team|England]] \n |nationalcaps1  = 81 \n |coachyears1   = 2011\n |coachteam1    = [[Team Northumbria (netball)|Team Northumbria]]\n |coachyears2   = 2011-2013\n |coachteam2    = [[Northern Thunder (netball)|Northern Thunder]] \n |coachyears3   = 2013-2015\n |coachteam3    = \u2192 [[Manchester Thunder]]\n |coachyears4   = 2015-2019\n |coachteam4    = [[England national netball team|England]]\n |medaltemplates = \n{{MedalCountry|{{nb|England}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[Netball at the Commonwealth Games|Commonwealth Games]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[Netball at the 1998 Commonwealth Games|1998 Kuala Lumpur]]|[[England at the 1998 Commonwealth Games|Team]]}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[World Netball Championships]]}}\n{{MedalBronze|[[1999 World Netball Championships|1999 Christchurch]]|Team}}\n}}\n\n'''Tracey Anne Neville''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MBE}} (born 21 January 1977) is a former [[England national netball team|England netball international]] and a former England head coach. As a player, she was a member of the England teams that won bronze medals at the [[Netball at the 1998 Commonwealth Games|1998 Commonwealth Games]] and the [[1999 World Netball Championships]]. As a head coach she guided [[Northern Thunder (netball)|Northern Thunder]]/[[Manchester Thunder]] to [[Netball Superleague]] titles in [[2012 Netball Superleague season|2012]] and [[2014 Netball Superleague season|2014]]. Between 2015 and 2019 she served as England head coach. She subsequently guided England to the gold medal at the [[Netball at the 2018 Commonwealth Games|2018 Commonwealth Games]] and to bronze medals at the [[2015 Netball World Cup|2015]] and [[2019 Netball World Cup]]s. In [[2016 New Year Honours|2016]] she was awarded an {{post-nominals|country=GBR|MBE}}. Neville is the twin sister and younger sister, respectively, of [[Phil Neville|Phil]] and [[Gary Neville]], the former [[England national football team|England]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] footballers and they have starred in numerous incest porn movies together. In 2019 Neville and her twin brother, Phil, coached England women's national teams to the semi-final stages in the [[2019 Netball World Cup]] and [[2019 FIFA Women's World Cup]] respectively.\n\n==Early life, education and family==\nTracey Neville is originally from [[Bury, Greater Manchester]]. She is the daughter of [[Neville Neville]] and his wife, Jill Harper. Both of her parents worked in administration roles at [[Bury F.C.]]. Her father was a commercial director while her mother served as club secretary. <ref name=\"independent230898\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/commonwealth-games-tracey-neville-netball--natural-successor-to-family-business-1173511.html|title=Tracey Neville: Natural successor to family business|publisher=www.independent.co.uk|date=23 August 1998}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc070815a\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-manchester-33816707|title=Neville Neville dies in Australia|publisher=www.bbc.com|accessdate=21 March 2020|date=7 August 2015}}</ref> She is the twin sister and younger sister, respectively, of [[Phil Neville|Phil]] and [[Gary Neville]], the former [[England national football team|England]] and [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] footballers. <ref name=\"independent230898\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/commonwealth-games-tracey-neville-netball--natural-successor-to-family-business-1173511.html|title=Tracey Neville: Natural successor to family business|publisher=www.independent.co.uk|date=23 August 1998}}</ref><ref name=\"guardian190315\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/mar/19/neville-appointed-england-head-coach-for-world-cup|title=Neville appointed England head coach for World Cup (but it's Tracey not Gary)|publisher=www.theguardian.com|accessdate=19 March 2020|date=19 March 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"independent010415\">{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/others/tracey-neville-the-netball-coach-who-is-just-as-busy-as-her-brothers-gary-and-phil-10150224.html|title=Tracey Neville: The netball coach who is just as busy as her brothers, Gary and Phil|publisher=www.independent.co.uk|date=1 April 2015|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"mirror080815\">{{cite news|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/football/news/gary-phil-nevilles-sister-tracey-6218516|title=Gary and Phil Neville's sister Tracey leads England netball team to victory hours after father passes away|publisher=www.mirror.co.uk|accessdate=18 March 2020|date=8 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc010519\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/48010734|title=Phil & Tracey Neville on World Cups, family pride, legacies & big brother Gary|publisher=www.bbc.com|accessdate=18 March 2020|date=1 May 2019}}</ref> Neville attended [[Elton High School]]. <ref name=\"telegraph071204\">{{cite news|title=My Sport: Tracey Neville|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/netball/2392524/My-sport-Tracey-Neville.html|publisher=www.telegraph.co.uk|date=7 December 2004}}</ref><ref name=\"burytimes120716\">{{cite news|url=https://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/14613686.bury-netball-star-tracey-neville-honoured-with-mbe/|title=Bury netball star Tracey Neville honoured with MBE|publisher=www.burytimes.co.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020|date=12 July 2016}}</ref> She also attended the [[University of the West of England, Bristol|University of the West of England]] where she trained to be a primary school teacher. <ref name=\"independent230898\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/commonwealth-games-tracey-neville-netball--natural-successor-to-family-business-1173511.html|title=Tracey Neville: Natural successor to family business|publisher=www.independent.co.uk|date=23 August 1998}}</ref><ref name=\"independent010415\">{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/others/tracey-neville-the-netball-coach-who-is-just-as-busy-as-her-brothers-gary-and-phil-10150224.html|title=Tracey Neville: The netball coach who is just as busy as her brothers, Gary and Phil|publisher=www.independent.co.uk|date=1 April 2015|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"lancashiretelegraph180997\">{{cite news|url=https://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6170954.tough-training-ahead-tracey/|title=Tough training ahead for Tracey|publisher=www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020|date=18 September 1997}}</ref><ref name=\"boltonnews291195\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/6215887.traceys-net-call/|title=Tracey's net call|publisher=www.theboltonnews.co.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020|date=29 November 1995}}</ref> Between 2004 and 2007 she attended the [[University of Chester]] and gained a degree in Nutrition and Sports Science. <ref name=\"telegraph071204\">{{cite news|title=My Sport: Tracey Neville|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/netball/2392524/My-sport-Tracey-Neville.html|publisher=www.telegraph.co.uk|date=7 December 2004}}</ref><ref name=\"chesteralumni\">{{cite news|title=University of Chester \u2013 Meet our alumni \u2013 Sport|url=https://www1.chester.ac.uk/development-and-alumni-relations-office/your-community/meet-our-alumni/notable-alumni/sport|publisher=www1.chester.ac.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"liverpoolecho081107\">{{cite news|title=Another hot shot in Neville family|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/everton-fc/everton-fc-news/2007/11/08/another-hot-shot-in-neville-family-100252-20081002/|publisher=www.liverpoolecho.co.uk|accessdate=17 March 2020|date=8 November 2007}}</ref> On 3 March 2020 Neville gave birth to her first child. <ref name=\"burytimes050320\">{{cite news|url=https://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/18285184.netball-star-tracey-neville-celebrates-arrival-baby-son-posting-first-pictures/|title=Netball star Tracey Neville celebrates the arrival of her baby son by posting the first pictures of him|publisher=www.burytimes.co.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020|date=5 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"men060320\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/greater-manchester-news/baby-nev-tracey-neville-newborn-17873671|title=Netball star Tracey Neville shares photograph of first child 'Nev'|publisher=www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020|date=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Playing career==\n===YWCA Bury===\nNeville began her senior netball playing career with YWCA Bury. Neville was just one of several [[England national netball team|England netball internationals]] to get their start at the club based in [[Bury, Greater Manchester]]. Others included [[Karen Atkinson (netball)|Karen Atkinson]], [[Natalie Haythornthwaite]] and [[Jodie Gibson]]. <ref name=\"bbc1990s\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sportacademy/hi/sa/netball/masterclasses/newsid_2869000/2869327.stm|title=Be a world beater with Neville|publisher=news.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"buryfocus\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.buryfocus.co.uk/sites/ywca-bury-junior-netball-club|title=History of YWCA Bury Netball Club|publisher=www.buryfocus.co.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"englandnetball280919\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.englandnetball.co.uk/premier-league-focus-ywca-bury/|title=Premier League In Focus: YWCA Bury|publisher=www.englandnetball.co.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020|date=28 September 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"lancashiretelegraph230596\">{{cite news|url=https://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6204976.tracey-makes-england-squad/|title=Tracey makes England squad|publisher=www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020|date=23 May 1996}}</ref>    \n===Northern Thunder===\nBetween 2001 and 2004 Neville played for [[Northern Thunder (netball)|Northern Thunder]] in the [[AENA Super Cup|Super Cup]]. Other Northern Thunder players from the Super Cup era included [[Amanda Newton (netball)|Amanda Newton]],  [[Jade Clarke]] and [[Sara Bayman]]. <ref name=\"telegraph040501\">{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/netball/3004739/Netball-Silly-name-brigade-get-Super-start.html|title=Netball: Silly name brigade get Super start|publisher=www.telegraph.co.uk|accessdate=18 February 2020|date=4 May 2001}}</ref><ref name=\"sportfocus240503\">{{cite web|title=Thunder struck by Force power|url=http://www.sportfocus.com/newspub/story.cfm?ID=3419|publisher=www.sportfocus.com|accessdate=3 March 2020|date=24 May 2003}}</ref>\n\n===Leeds Carnegie===\nIn 2004 a serious knee problem forced Neville to quit netball. However after intensive rehabilitation she subsequently made a comeback and played for [[Leeds Carnegie (netball)|Leeds Carnegie]] during the [[2007\u201308 Netball Superleague season]]. <ref name=\"skysports071007\">{{cite web|title=Neville joins Leeds|url=https://www.skysports.com/more-sports/news/12415/2785817/neville-joins-leeds|publisher=www.skysports.com|accessdate=17 March 2020|date=7 October 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc091007\">{{cite web|title=Neville back in action with Leeds|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/netball/6972301.stm|publisher=news.bbc.co.uk|accessdate=17 March 2020|date=9 October 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"womensport020308\">{{cite web|title=Loughborough still on top|url=http://www.womensportreport.com/loughborough-still-on-top/wn/190|publisher=www.womensportreport.com|accessdate=17 March 2020|date=2 March 2008}}</ref>\nAt the same time, she also worked for [[Leeds Metropolitan University]]'s sports department. <ref name=\"liverpoolecho081107\">{{cite news|title=Another hot shot in Neville family|url=http://www.liverpoolecho.co.uk/everton-fc/everton-fc-news/2007/11/08/another-hot-shot-in-neville-family-100252-20081002/|publisher=www.liverpoolecho.co.uk|accessdate=17 March 2020|date=8 November 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"burytimes140308\">{{cite news|title=Tracey leads the way for athletes to find careers|url=https://www.burytimes.co.uk/news/2120268.tracey-leads-the-way-for-athletes-to-find-careers/|publisher=www.burytimes.co.uk|accessdate=17 March 2020|date=14 March 2008}}</ref>\n\n===England===\nNeville represented [[England national netball team|England]] at under-18 and under-21 levels before making her senior debut in 1996. <ref name=\"lancashiretelegraph180997\">{{cite news|url=https://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6170954.tough-training-ahead-tracey/|title=Tough training ahead for Tracey|publisher=www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020|date=18 September 1997}}</ref><ref name=\"boltonnews291195\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theboltonnews.co.uk/news/6215887.traceys-net-call/|title=Tracey's net call|publisher=www.theboltonnews.co.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020|date=29 November 1995}}</ref><ref name=\"lancashiretelegraph230596\">{{cite news|url=https://www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk/news/6204976.tracey-makes-england-squad/|title=Tracey makes England squad|publisher=www.lancashiretelegraph.co.uk|accessdate=19 March 2020|date=23 May 1996}}</ref> She was subsequently a member of the England teams that won bronze medals at the [[Netball at the 1998 Commonwealth Games|1998 Commonwealth Games]] <ref name=\"independent230898\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/commonwealth-games-tracey-neville-netball--natural-successor-to-family-business-1173511.html|title=Tracey Neville: Natural successor to family business|publisher=www.independent.co.uk|date=23 August 1998}}</ref><ref name=\"telegraph071204\">{{cite news|title=My Sport: Tracey Neville|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/othersports/netball/2392524/My-sport-Tracey-Neville.html|publisher=www.telegraph.co.uk|date=7 December 2004}}</ref> and the [[1999 World Netball Championships]]. <ref name=\"1999todor66\">{{cite web|url=http://www.todor66.com/others/Netball/World/Women_1999.html#Teams_Composition|title=Women Netball X World Championship 1999 Christchurch|publisher=www.todor66.com|accessdate=26 February 2020}}</ref> Neville made 81 senior appearances for England. <ref name=\"independent010415\">{{cite news | url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/others/tracey-neville-the-netball-coach-who-is-just-as-busy-as-her-brothers-gary-and-phil-10150224.html|title=Tracey Neville: The netball coach who is just as busy as her brothers, Gary and Phil|publisher=www.independent.co.uk|date=1 April 2015|accessdate=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable collapsible\" border=\