{flag|Grenada}}|{{flag|Guyana}}|{{flag|Honduras}}|{{flag|Jamaica}}|{{flag|Montserrat}}|{{flag|Nicaragua}}|{{flag|Saint Kitts and Nevis}}|{{flag|Saint Vincent and the Grenadines}}|{{flag|Trinidad and Tobago}}|{{flag|Turks and Caicos Islands|name=Turks and Caicos}}|{{flag|United States}}\n}}\n|footnotes  =\n}}\n\n'''British America''' refers to the [[British Empire]]'s colonial territories in America from 1607 to 1783. These colonies were formally known as '''British America''' and the '''British West Indies''' before the [[Thirteen Colonies]] fought for their independence in the [[American Revolutionary War]] (1775\u20131783) and formed the United States of America.<ref>{{cite web|title=A Summary View of the Rights of British America \u2013 Thomas Jefferson|url=http://press-pubs.uchicago.edu/founders/documents/v1ch14s10.html}}</ref> After the [[American Revolution]], the term [[British North America]] referred to the remainder of Great Britain's Canadian possessions. That term was first used informally in 1783, but it was uncommon before the ''Report on the Affairs of British North America'' (1839), generally known as the ''[[Durham Report]]''.\n\nBritish America gained large amounts of territory with the [[Treaty of Paris (1763)]], which ended the [[French and Indian War]] in America and the [[Seven Years' War]] in Europe. At the start of the Revolutionary War in 1775, the British Empire included 23 colonies and territories on the North American continent. The [[Treaty of Paris (1783)]] ended the war, and Britain lost much of this territory to the newly formed United States. In addition, Britain ceded [[East Florida|East]] and [[West Florida]] to the Kingdom of Spain, which in turn ceded them to the United States in 1821. Most of the remaining colonies to the north formed Canada in 1867, with the [[Dominion of Newfoundland]] joining in 1949.\n\n== History ==\n{{Main|English overseas possessions#The Americas}}\n{{further|First British Empire}}\n[[File:Senex, Price, and Maxwell North America 1710 UTA.jpg|thumb|British map of North America, 1710]]\n\nA number of English colonies were established in America between 1606 and 1670 by individuals and companies whose investors expected to reap rewards from their speculation. They were granted commercial charters by [[James VI and I|King James I]], [[Charles I of England|King Charles I]], Parliament, and [[Charles II of England|King Charles II]]. The [[London Company]] founded the first permanent settlement in 1607 on the [[James River (Virginia)|James River]] at [[Jamestown, Virginia]] upstream from [[Chesapeake Bay]]. This was followed in 1620 when the Pilgrims established the [[Plymouth settlement]] in [[New England]]. English Catholics settled the [[Province of Maryland]] in 1634, with [[Cecil Calvert, 2nd Baron Baltimore|Cecilus Calvert, second Lord Baltimore]].\n\nA state department in London known as the [[Southern Department (United Kingdom)|Southern Department]] governed all the colonies beginning in 1660, as well as a committee of the [[Privy Council of England|Privy Council]] called the [[Board of Trade and Plantations]]. In 1768, Parliament created a specific [[Colonial Office#First Colonial Office (1768\u20131782)|state department]] for America, but it was disbanded in 1782 when the [[Home Office]] took responsibility for the remaining possessions of [[British North America]] in eastern Canada, the Floridas, and the West Indies.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.com/en/article/colonial-office/ |title=Colonial Office |last=Foulds |first=Nancy Brown |website=The Canadian Encyclopedia |language=en |access-date=2018-07-07}}</ref>\n\n== North American colonies in 1775 ==\n\nThe [[Thirteen Colonies]] that became the original states of the United States:\n\n:; [[New England Colonies]]:\n:*[[Province of Massachusetts Bay]]\n:*[[Province of New Hampshire]]\n:*[[Colony of Rhode Island and Providence Plantations]]<ref name=\"King Charles II Rhode Island Charter\" /><ref name=\"Church History \u2013 King Charles II Rhode Island Charter\" />\n:*[[Connecticut Colony]]\n\n[[File:A view of Fort George with the city of New York, from the SW.jpg|thumb|A view of [[Fort Amsterdam|Fort George]] and the city of [[New York City|New York]] c. 1731]]\n:; [[Middle Colonies]]:\n:*[[Province of New York]]\n:*[[Province of New Jersey]]\n:*[[Province of Pennsylvania]]\n:*[[Delaware Colony]]\n\n:; [[Southern Colonies]]:\n:*[[Province of Maryland]]\n:*[[Colony of Virginia]]\n:*[[Province of North Carolina]]\n:*[[Province of South Carolina]]\n:*[[Province of Georgia]]\n\nColonies and territories that became part of Canada:\n\n:*[[Province of Quebec (1763\u20131791)|Province of Quebec]] northeast of the [[Great Lakes]] (including [[Labrador]] until 1791)\n:*[[Nova Scotia]] (including [[New Brunswick]] until 1784)\n:*[[Prince Edward Island|Island of St. John]]\n:*[[Colony of Newfoundland]]\n:*[[Rupert's Land]]\n:*[[North-Western Territory]]\n:*[[British Arctic Territories]]\n\nColonies and territories that were ceded to Spain or the United States in 1783:\n\n:*Province of [[East Florida]] (Spanish 1783\u20131823, U.S. after 1823)\n:*Province of [[West Florida]] (Spanish 1783-1823, U.S. after 1823)\n:*[[Indian Reserve (1763)|Indian Reserve]] (U.S. after 1783)\n:*[[Province of Quebec (1763\u20131791)|Province of Quebec]] southwest of the [[Great Lakes]] (U.S. after 1783)\n\n== Colonies in the Caribbean, Mid-Atlantic, and South America in 1783 ==\n:*[[Bermuda]]\n:; Divisions of the [[British Leeward Islands]]:\n:*[[Saint Kitts|Saint Christopher]] (de facto capital)\n:*[[Antigua]]\n:*[[Barbuda]]\n:*[[British Virgin Islands]]\n:*[[Montserrat]]\n:*[[Nevis]]\n:*[[Anguilla]]\n\n:; [[British West Indies, Jamaica and dependencies|Island of Jamaica and its dependencies]]:\n:*Island of [[Jamaica]]\n:*Settlement of Belize in [[British Honduras]]\n:*[[Mosquito Coast]]\n:*[[Bay Islands (department)|Bay Islands]]\n:*[[Cayman Islands]]\n\n:; Other possessions in the [[British Windward Islands]]:\n:*Island of [[Barbados]]\n:*Island of [[Grenada]]\n:*[[Saint Vincent and the Grenadines|Island of St. Vincent]]\n:*Island of [[Tobago]] (detached from Grenada in 1768)\n:*Island of [[Dominica]] (detached from Grenada in 1770)\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|British Empire|History|Canada|North America|United States|Caribbean}}\n* [[British colonization of the Americas]]\n* [[British North America Acts]]\n* [[British overseas territories]]\n* [[Colonial history of the United States]]\n* [[Evolution of the British Empire]]\n* [[Former colonies and territories in Canada]]\n\n== Citations ==\n{{Reflist\n| refs =\n<ref name=\"King Charles II Rhode Island Charter\">{{cite web\n| url         = http://sos.ri.gov/library/history/charter/\n| title       = Rhode Island Royal Charter of 1663\n| author      =\n| date        =\n| month       =\n| year        =\n| work        = sos.ri.gov\n| publisher   = [[Secretary of State of Rhode Island]]\n| format      =\n| archiveurl  =\n| archivedate =\n| accessdate  = 14 April 2011\n| quote       =\n| postscript  = .\n}}</ref>\n\n<ref name=\"Church History \u2013 King Charles II Rhode Island Charter\">{{cite web\n| url         = http://www.christianity.com/ChurchHistory/11630142/\n| title       = Charles II Granted Rhode Island New Charter\n| author      =\n| date        = 8 July 1663\n| month       =\n| year        =\n| work        = christianity.com\n| publisher   = [[Christianity.com]]\n| format      =\n| archiveurl  =\n| archivedate =\n| accessdate  = 14 April 2011\n| quote       =\n| postscript  = .\n}}</ref>\n\n<!-- the two entries below do nothing: is it necessary to define \"British\" as the UK did not formally come into being until the Act of Union 1707? See also Union_of_the_Crowns#British -->\nhttp://dictionary.reference.com/browse/British\nhttp://www.merriam-webster.com/dictionary/british\n}}\n\n{{coord missing|North America}}\n\n[[Category:1607 establishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:1783 disestablishments in North America]]\n[[Category:1783 disestablishments in the British Empire]]\n[[Category:British colonization of the Americas]]\n[[Category:British North America]]\n[[Category:Colonial United States (British)]]\n[[Category:Colonization history of the United States]]\n[[Category:English-speaking countries and territories]]\n[[Category:History of the Caribbean]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1607]]\n", "name_user": "Blairall", "label": "safe", "comment": "revised a link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/British_America"}
{"title_page": "Miroslav Vitou\u0161", "text_new": "{{short description|Czech bassguitarist, jazz musician and contrabassist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Miroslav Vitou\u0161\n| image               = Miroslav Vitou\u0161.jpg\n| caption             = Vitou\u0161 in 2014\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Miroslav Ladislav Vitou\u0161\n| birth_place       = [[Prague]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1947|12|06}}\n| genre               = [[Jazz]], [[jazz fusion]], [[funk]]\n| instrument        = Double bass, bass guitar\n| occupation        = Musician, songwriter\n| years_active      = 1962\u2013present\n| label                 = [[Freedom Records|Freedom]]\n| associated_acts = [[Weather Report]]\n| website            = {{URL|miroslavvitous.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Miroslav Ladislav Vitou\u0161''' (born 6 December 1947) is a Czech [[jazz]] bassist.\n== Biography ==\nBorn in [[Prague]], he began the violin at age six<ref name=\"AAJ\">{{cite web|title=A Fireside Chat With Miroslav Vitous |publisher=All About Jazz |first=Fred |last=Jung |url=http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/article.php?id=619 |date =10 October 2003 |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> and started playing piano at age ten and bass at fourteen. As a young man in Europe, Vitou\u0161 was a competitive swimmer. One of his early music groups was the Junior Trio with his brother Alan on drums and [[Jan Hammer]] on keyboards. He studied music at the [[Prague Conservatory]] (under Franti\u0161ek Po\u0161ta),<ref>{{cite web|title=Miroslav Vitous: It Comes Down to Taste |publisher=All About Jazz |first=Paul |last=Olsen |url=http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/article.php?id=27881 |date=7 January 2008 |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> and won a music contest in Vienna that gave him a scholarship to the [[Berklee College of Music]].<ref name=\"AAJ\" />\n\nIn 1967, in Chicago, [[Miles Davis]] saw Vitou\u0161 playing with [[Clark Terry]] and invited him to join his group for a residency at [[The Village Gate]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ecmrecords.com/Background/2013.php |title=ECM |work=ecmrecords.com |accessdate=23 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224010021/http://www.ecmrecords.com/Background/2013.php |archive-date=24 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nHis 1970 Embryo/Atlantic album ''[[Infinite Search]]''<ref name=\"AAJ\" /> aka \"Mountain In The Clouds\" was recorded with [[John McLaughlin (musician)|John McLaughlin]], [[Herbie Hancock]], [[Jack DeJohnette]], and [[Joe Henderson]]. That year, he also recorded \"[[Purple]]\" for Columbia Records with McLaughlin, Billy Cobham and Joe Zawinul.\n\nHe has also worked with [[Chick Corea]], [[Larry Coryell]], [[Jan Garbarek]], [[Freddie Hubbard]], [[Michel Petrucciani]], [[Terje Rypdal]], [[Wayne Shorter]], and [[Joe Zawinul]]\n\nIn 1970 he was a founding member of the group [[Weather Report]].<ref name=\"AAJ\" /> In 1973 he was replaced by [[Alphonso Johnson]]. He stated, \"I enjoyed the beginning of it very much, but it turned into a little bit of a drag in the end because Joe Zawinul wanted to go in another direction. The band was seeking success and fame and they basically changed their music to go a commercial way into a black funk thing\". He also felt aggrieved financially. \"I was an equal partner and basically, I didn't get anything. We had a corporation together that was completely ignored. If you have a company and three people own it, and then two people say 'Okay, we don't want to work like this anymore. It's just two of us now', normally, they break down the stock and pay off the third person\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Prasad |first1=Anil |title=Miroslav Vitous \u2013 Freeing the Muse|url=http://www.innerviews.org/inner/vitous.html |website=Inner Views |accessdate=2015-01-07}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Roy Haynes Quintet 1981.jpg|left|thumb|Vitous with Roy Haynes Quintet 1981]]\nIn 1981 he performed at the [[Woodstock Jazz Festival]] held in celebration of the tenth anniversary of the [[Creative Music Studio]]. In 1984 he collaborated with [[Stanley Clarke]].<ref>1984 Sydney Town Hall, producer Ian Davis (ABC radio)</ref> In 1988 Vitou\u0161 moved back to Europe to concentrate on composing but nonetheless continued to perform in festivals.\n\nIn 2001, Vitou\u0161 reunited with Corea and Haynes (as the Now He Sings, Now He Sobs trio) for a concert in a series entitled \"Rendezvous in New York\" in celebration of Corea's 60th birthday. The [[Rendezvous in New York|album of the same name]] came out in 2003 and earned Corea a [[Grammy Award for Best Improvised Jazz Solo]] for the composition \"Matrix\".<ref name=\"grm\">{{cite web | url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=chick+corea&title=&year=2003&genre=16 | title=Past Winners Search | publisher=Grammy.com | accessdate=24 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== As leader ===\n* 1970 ''[[Infinite Search]]'' (a.k.a. ''Mountain in the Clouds'') ([[Embryo Records|Embryo]]) \n* 1970 ''Purple'' (CBS/Sony)\n* 1976 ''Majesty Music'' ([[Arista Records|Arista]])\n* 1976 ''Magical Shepherd'' ([[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]])\n* 1977 ''Miroslav'' ([[Freedom Records|Freedom]]) \n* 1978 ''Guardian Angels'' \n* 1980 ''[[First Meeting (Miroslav Vitou\u0161 album)|First Meeting]]'' ([[ECM Records|ECM]])\n* 1981 ''To Be Continued'' with Terje Rypdal, Jack DeJohnette (ECM)\n* 1982 ''Trio Music'' with Chick Corea, Roy Haynes (ECM)\n* 1983 ''[[Journey's End (album)|Journey's End]]'' (ECM)\n* 1986 ''[[Emergence (Miroslav Vitous album)|Emergence]]'' (ECM) \n* 1986 ''Trio Music Live in Europe'' with Chick Corea, Roy Haynes (ECM)\n* 1993 ''[[Atmos (album)|Atmos]]'' (ECM) with [[Jan Garbarek]]\n* 2003 ''[[Universal Syncopations]]'' (ECM) \n* 2007 ''[[Universal Syncopations II]]'' (ECM) \n* 2009 ''[[Remembering Weather Report]]'' (ECM)\n* 2014 ''[[Miroslav Vitous Group]]'' (ECM)\n* 2015 ''Wings'' with [[Adam Pieronczyk]]\n* 2016 ''Music of Weather Report'' (ECM)\n* 2016 ''Ziljabu Nights'' (Intuition)<ref name=\"AM discog\">{{cite web |title=Miroslav Vitous {{!}} Album Discography |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/miroslav-vitous-mn0000499683/discography |website=AllMusic |accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref>\n* 2017 ''Ad-lib Orbits'' with [[Adam Pieronczyk]] (Jazzsound)\n* 2019 ''Live at NOSPR'' with [[Adam Pieronczyk]] (Jazzsound)\n\n=== As sideman ===\n'''With [[Franco Ambrosetti]]'''\n*''[[Light Breeze]]'' (Enja, 1998)\n\n'''With [[Roy Ayers]]'''\n*''[[Stoned Soul Picnic (Roy Ayers album)|Stoned Soul Picnic]]'' (Atlantic, 1968)\n\n'''With [[Chick Corea]]'''\n*''[[Now He Sings, Now He Sobs]]'' ([[Solid State Records (jazz label)|Solid State]], 1968)\n*''[[Trio Music]]'' (ECM, 1981)\n*''[[Trio Music Live in Europe]]'' (ECM, 1984)\n*''[[Rendezvous in New York]]'' ([[Stretch Records|Stretch]], 2003)\n\n'''With [[Larry Coryell]]'''\n*''[[Spaces (Larry Coryell album)|Spaces]]'' (Vanguard, 1970) \n*''[[Dedicated to Bill Evans and Scott LaFaro]]'' (Jazzpoint, 1987)\n\n'''With [[Jack DeJohnette]]'''\n*''[[The DeJohnette Complex]]'' ([[Milestone Records|Milestone]], 1969)\n\n'''With [[Jan Garbarek]]'''\n*''[[StAR (album)|StAR]]'' (ECM, 1991)\n\n'''With [[Laszlo Gardony]]'''\n*''The Secret'' ([[Antilles Records|Antilles]], 1988)\n\n'''With [[Stan Getz]]'''\n*''[[The Song Is You (Stan Getz album)|The Song Is You]]'' (1969)\n\n'''With [[Herbie Mann]]'''\n*''[[Windows Opened]]'' (Atlantic, 1968)\n*''[[The Inspiration I Feel]]'' (Atlantic, 1968)\n*''[[Memphis Underground]]'' (Atlantic, 1969)\n*''[[Stone Flute]]'' (Embryo, 1970)\n*''[[Live at the Whisky a Go Go (Herbie Mann album)|Live at the Whisky a Go Go]]'' (Atlantic, 1969)\n\n'''With [[Terje Rypdal]]'''\n*''[[Terje Rypdal / Miroslav Vitous / Jack DeJohnette]]'' (ECM, 1978)\n*''[[To Be Continued (Terje Rypdal album)|To Be Continued]]'' (ECM, 1981)\n\n'''With [[Sadao Watanabe (musician)|Sadao Watanabe]]'''\n*''[[Round Trip (Sadao Watanabe album)|Round Trip]]'' (1974)\n\n'''With [[Weather Report]]'''\n*''[[Weather Report (1971 album)|Weather Report]]'' (Columbia, 1971)\n*''[[I Sing the Body Electric (album)|I Sing the Body Electric]]'' (Columbia, 1972)\n*''[[Live in Tokyo (Weather Report album)|Live in Tokyo]]'' (Columbia, 1972)\n*''[[Sweetnighter]]'' (Columbia, 1973)\n*''[[Mysterious Traveller]]'' (Columbia, 1974)\n\n== References ==\n{{Portal|United States|Jazz}}\n{{commons category|Miroslav Vitou\u0161}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071128042302/http://www.miroslavvitous.com/ Official site]\n*[http://andreyhenkin.com/discographies.htm/vitous.htm/vitous%20discography.htm Miroslav Vitous Discography 1964\u201374]\n*[http://news.allaboutjazz.com/uys-miroslav-vitous-and-jean-luc-ponty-interviews.php#.U5WILC9lybI Miroslav Vitous video interview at Allaboutjazz.com]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110707214612/http://www.bass-musician-magazine.com/General/bass-musician-magazine-detail.asp?year=2009&month=8&article-id=517801068 Conversation With Miroslav Vitous, 8/01/2009]\n* [http://www.penceland.com/cgi-bin/play_flv.pl?filename=Miroslav_Vitous%20and%20Stanley_Clarke%20-%20Agitation.flv&width=500&height=375&title=Miroslav%20Vitous%20and%20Stanley%20Clarke%20-%20Agitation \"Agitation\", with Stanley Clarke]\n\n{{Miroslav Vitou\u0161}}\n{{Weather Report}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vitou\u0161, Miroslav}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Prague]]\n[[Category:Avant-garde jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Jazz fusion musicians]]\n[[Category:Berklee College of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century double-bassists]]\n[[Category:21st-century double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Czech jazz double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Male double-bassists]]\n[[Category:Weather Report members]]\n[[Category:Freedom Records artists]]\n[[Category:Czech emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:20th-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:Male jazz musicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Czech bassguitarist, jazz musician and contrabassist}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Miroslav Vitou\u0161\n| image               = Miroslav Vitou\u0161.jpg\n| caption             = Vitou\u0161 in 2014\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Miroslav Ladislav Vitou\u0161\n| birth_place       = [[Prague]], [[Czechoslovakia]]\n| birth_date        = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1947|12|06}}\n| genre               = [[Jazz]], [[jazz fusion]], [[funk]]\n| instrument        = Double bass, bass guitar\n| occupation        = Musician, songwriter\n| years_active      = 1962\u2013present\n| label                 = [[Freedom Records|Freedom]]\n| associated_acts = [[Weather Report]]\n| website            = {{URL|miroslavvitous.com}}\n}}\n\n'''Miroslav Ladislav Vitou\u0161''' (born 6 December 1947) is a Czech [[jazz]] bassist who has had an extensive career in the US.\n\n== Biography ==\nBorn in [[Prague]], he began the violin at age six<ref name=\"AAJ\">{{cite web|title=A Fireside Chat With Miroslav Vitous |publisher=All About Jazz |first=Fred |last=Jung |url=http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/article.php?id=619 |date =10 October 2003 |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> and started playing piano at age ten and bass at fourteen. As a young man in Europe, Vitou\u0161 was a competitive swimmer. One of his early music groups was the Junior Trio with his brother Alan on drums and [[Jan Hammer]] on keyboards. He studied music at the [[Prague Conservatory]] (under Franti\u0161ek Po\u0161ta),<ref>{{cite web|title=Miroslav Vitous: It Comes Down to Taste |publisher=All About Jazz |first=Paul |last=Olsen |url=http://www.allaboutjazz.com/php/article.php?id=27881 |date=7 January 2008 |accessdate=2010-06-20}}</ref> and won a music contest in Vienna that gave him a scholarship to the [[Berklee College of Music]].<ref name=\"AAJ\" />\n\nIn 1967, in Chicago, [[Miles Davis]] saw Vitou\u0161 playing with [[Clark Terry]] and invited him to join his group for a residency at [[The Village Gate]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ecmrecords.com/Background/2013.php |title=ECM |work=ecmrecords.com |accessdate=23 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150224010021/http://www.ecmrecords.com/Background/2013.php |archive-date=24 February 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n \nHis 1970 Embryo/Atlantic album ''[[Infinite Search]]''<ref name=\"AAJ\" /> aka \u201cMountain In The Clouds\u201d was recorded with [[John McLaughlin (musician)|John McLaughlin]], [[Herbie Hancock]], [[Jack DeJohnette]], and [[Joe Henderson]]. That year, he also recorded \u201c[[Purple]]\u201d for Columbia Records with McLaughlin, Billy Cobham and Joe Zawinul.\n\nHe has also worked with [[Chick Corea]], [[Larry Coryell]], [[Jan Garbarek]], [[Freddie Hubbard]], [[Michel Petrucciani]], [[Terje Rypdal]], [[Wayne Shorter]], and [[Joe Zawinul]]\n\nIn 1970 he was a founding member of the group [[Weather Report]].<ref name=\"AAJ\" /> In 1973 he was replaced by [[Alphonso Johnson]]. He stated, \"I enjoyed the beginning of it very much, but it turned into a little bit of a drag in the end because Joe Zawinul wanted to go in another direction. The band was seeking success and fame and they basically changed their music to go a commercial way into a black funk thing\". He also felt aggrieved financially. \"I was an equal partner and basically, I didn't get anything. We had a corporation together that was completely ignored. If you have a company and three people own it, and then two people say 'Okay, we don't want to work like this anymore. It's just two of us now', normally, they break down the stock and pay off the third person\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Prasad |first1=Anil |title=Miroslav Vitous \u2013 Freeing the Muse|url=http://www.innerviews.org/inner/vitous.html |website=Inner Views |accessdate=2015-01-07}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Roy Haynes Quintet 1981.jpg|left|thumb|Vitous with Roy Haynes Quintet 1981]]\nIn 1981 he performed at the [[Woodstock Jazz Festival]] held in celebration of the tenth anniversary of the [[Creative Music Studio]]. In 1984 he collaborated with [[Stanley Clarke]].<ref>1984 Sydney Town Hall, producer Ian Davis (ABC radio)</ref> In 1988 Vitou\u0161 moved back to Europe to concentrate on composing but nonetheless continued to perform in festivals.\n\nIn 2001, Vitou\u0161 reunited with Corea and Haynes (as the Now He Sings, Now He Sobs trio) for a concert in a series entitled \"Rendezvous in New York\" in celebration of Corea's 60th birthday. The [[Rendezvous in New York|album of the same name]] came out in 2003 and earned Corea a [[Grammy Award for Best Improvised Jazz Solo]] for the composition \"Matrix\".<ref name=\"grm\">{{cite web | url=http://www.grammy.com/nominees/search?artist=chick+corea&title=&year=2003&genre=16 | title=Past Winners Search | publisher=Grammy.com | accessdate=24 March 2012}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== As leader ===\n* 1970 ''[[Infinite Search]]'' (a.k.a. ''Mountain in the Clouds'') ([[Embryo Records|Embryo]]) \n* 1970 ''Purple'' (CBS/Sony)\n* 1976 ''Majesty Music'' ([[Arista Records|Arista]])\n* 1976 ''Magical Shepherd'' ([[Warner Bros. Records|Warner Bros.]])\n* 1977 ''Miroslav'' ([[Freedom Records|Freedom]]) \n* 1978 ''Guardian Angels'' \n* 1980 ''[[First Meeting (Miroslav Vitou\u0161 album)|First Meeting]]'' ([[ECM Records|ECM]])\n* 1981 ''To Be Continued'' with Terje Rypdal, Jack DeJohnette (ECM)\n* 1982 ''Trio Music'' with Chick Corea, Roy Haynes (ECM)\n* 1983 ''[[Journey's End (album)|Journey's End]]'' (ECM)\n* 1986 ''[[Emergence (Miroslav Vitous album)|Emergence]]'' (ECM) \n* 1986 ''Trio Music Live in Europe'' with Chick Corea, Roy Haynes (ECM)\n* 1993 ''[[Atmos (album)|Atmos]]'' (ECM) with [[Jan Garbarek]]\n* 2003 ''[[Universal Syncopations]]'' (ECM) \n* 2007 ''[[Universal Syncopations II]]'' (ECM) \n* 2009 ''[[Remembering Weather Report]]'' (ECM)\n* 2014 ''[[Miroslav Vitous Group]]'' (ECM)\n* 2015 ''Wings'' with [[Adam Pieronczyk]]\n* 2016 ''Music of Weather Report'' (ECM)\n* 2016 ''Ziljabu Nights'' (Intuition)<ref name=\"AM discog\">{{cite web |title=Miroslav Vitous {{!}} Album Discography |url=https://www.allmusic.com/artist/miroslav-vitous-mn0000499683/discography |website=AllMusic |accessdate=16 January 2019}}</ref>\n* 2017 ''Ad-lib Orbits'' with [[Adam Pieronczyk]] (Jazzsound)\n* 2019 ''Live at NOSPR'' with [[Adam Pieronczyk]] (Jazzsound)\n\n=== As sideman ===\n'''With [[Franco Ambrosetti]]'''\n*''[[Light Breeze]]'' (Enja, 1998)\n\n'''With [[Roy Ayers]]'''\n*''[[Stoned Soul Picnic (Roy Ayers album)|Stoned Soul Picnic]]'' (Atlantic, 1968)\n\n'''With [[Chick Corea]]'''\n*''[[Now He Sings, Now He Sobs]]'' ([[Solid State Records (jazz label)|Solid State]], 1968)\n*''[[Trio Music]]'' (ECM, 1981)\n*''[[Trio Music Live in Europe]]'' (ECM, 1984)\n*''[[Rendezvous in New York]]'' ([[Stretch Records|Stretch]], 2003)\n\n'''With [[Larry Coryell]]'''\n*''[[Spaces (Larry Coryell album)|Spaces]]'' (Vanguard, 1970) \n*''[[Dedicated to Bill Evans and Scott LaFaro]]'' (Jazzpoint, 1987)\n\n'''With [[Jack DeJohnette]]'''\n*''[[The DeJohnette Complex]]'' ([[Milestone Records|Milestone]], 1969)\n\n'''With [[Jan Garbarek]]'''\n*''[[StAR (album)|StAR]]'' (ECM, 1991)\n\n'''With [[Laszlo Gardony]]'''\n*''The Secret'' ([[Antilles Records|Antilles]], 1988)\n\n'''With [[Stan Getz]]'''\n*''[[The Song Is You (Stan Getz album)|The Song Is You]]'' (1969)\n\n'''With [[Herbie Mann]]'''\n*''[[Windows Opened]]'' (Atlantic, 1968)\n*''[[The Inspiration I Feel]]'' (Atlantic, 1968)\n*''[[Memphis Underground]]'' (Atlantic, 1969)\n*''[[Stone Flute]]'' (Embryo, 1970)\n*''[[Live at the Whisky a Go Go (Herbie Mann album)|Live at the Whisky a Go Go]]'' (Atlantic, 1969)\n\n'''With [[Terje Rypdal]]'''\n*''[[Terje Rypdal / Miroslav Vitous / Jack DeJohnette]]'' (ECM, 1978)\n*''[[To Be Continued (Terje Rypdal album)|To Be Continued]]'' (ECM, 1981)\n\n'''With [[Sadao Watanabe (musician)|Sadao Watanabe]]'''\n*''[[Round Trip (Sadao Watanabe album)|Round Trip]]'' (1974)\n\n'''With [[Weather Report]]'''\n*''[[Weather Report (1971 album)|Weather Report]]'' (Columbia, 1971)\n*''[[I Sing the Body Electric (album)|I Sing the Body Electric]]'' (Columbia, 1972)\n*''[[Live in Tokyo (Weather Report album)|Live in Tokyo]]'' (Columbia, 1972)\n*''[[Sweetnighter]]'' (Columbia, 1973)\n*''[[Mysterious Traveller]]'' (Columbia, 1974)\n\n== References ==\n{{Portal|United States|Jazz}}\n{{commons category|Miroslav Vitou\u0161}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071128042302/http://www.miroslavvitous.com/ Official site]\n*[http://andreyhenkin.com/discographies.htm/vitous.htm/vitous%20discography.htm Miroslav Vitous Discography 1964\u201374]\n*[http://news.allaboutjazz.com/uys-miroslav-vitous-and-jean-luc-ponty-interviews.php#.U5WILC9lybI Miroslav Vitous video interview at Allaboutjazz.com]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20110707214612/http://www.bass-musician-magazine.com/General/bass-musician-magazine-detail.asp?year=2009&month=8&article-id=517801068 Conversation With Miroslav Vitous, 8/01/2009]\n* [http://www.penceland.com/cgi-bin/play_flv.pl?filename=Miroslav_Vitous%20and%20Stanley_Clarke%20-%20Agitation.flv&width=500&height=375&title=Miroslav%20Vitous%20and%20Stanley%20Clarke%20-%20Agitation \"Agitation\", with Stanley Clarke]\n\n{{Miroslav Vitou\u0161}}\n{{Weather Report}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Vitou\u0161, Miroslav}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Prague]]\n[[Category:Avant-garde jazz musicians]]\n[[Category:Jazz fusion musicians]]\n[[Category:Berklee College of Music alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century double-bassists]]\n[[Category:21st-century double-bassi